{\pard\sb0\sa120\f0\fs22 The dispatcher is four lines: {\b look up the active format in the row's dict, call the function (or substitute the string), move on}. That's the {\b strategy pattern implemented functionally} \u8212? each strategy is a small pure function (or an {\f1\fs20\chshdng1\chcbpat8 re.sub} replacement string), chosen by dict key at runtime. No base class, no subclass hierarchy, no visitor.\par}
{\pard\sb0\sa120\f0\fs22 What this feels like when you edit the code:\par}
{\pard\sb36\sa36\li480\fi-360\f0\fs22 \u8226?  {\b Add a markdown feature} \u8594? add one row. (This is how {\f1\fs20\chshdng1\chcbpat8 <sub>}, {\f1\fs20\chshdng1\chcbpat8 <sup>}, {\f1\fs20\chshdng1\chcbpat8 <ins>}, and the emoji shortcode map were added.)\par}
{\pard\sb36\sa36\li480\fi-360\f0\fs22 \u8226?  {\b Add a new output format} \u8594? add one key to every row. Dispatcher doesn't change.\par}
{\pard\sb36\sa36\li480\fi-360\f0\fs22 \u8226?  {\b Tweak how bold renders in DOCX} \u8594? edit one cell. Other formats untouched.\par}
{\pard\sb36\sa36\li480\fi-360\f0\fs22 \u8226?  Rules run in {\b phases} (HTML strip \u8594? escapes \u8594? links/images \u8594? inline code stash \u8594? GitHub refs \u8594? formatting), so later rows can assume earlier phases have already happened.\par}
